        // for at least floor(r/2) - floor((l-1)/2) numbers.
        // This count is at least 1 if r >= 2 and l <= r.
        //
        // Consider any number x > 2.
        // The count of multiples of x in [l, r] is floor(r/x) - floor((l-1)/x).
        // The count of multiples of 2 in [l, r] is floor(r/2) - floor((l-1)/2).
        //
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, then there are at least two numbers in the range.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, then there must be at least one even number in the range.
        // For example, if l is odd, l+1 is even. If l is even, l is even.
        // So, the count for divisor 2 is always at least 1.
        //
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, the count of multiples of 2 is at least 1.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 3, the count of multiples of 2 is at least 2.
        //
        // For any x > 2, the count of its multiples in [l, r] is
        // floor(r/x) - floor((l-1)/x).
        // This count is always less than or equal to floor(r/2) - floor((l-1)/2)
        // because x > 2 implies 1/x < 1/2, so r/x < r/2 and (l-1)/x < (l-1)/2.
        //
        // Specifically, if r - l + 1 >= 2, then 2 is a divisor for at least one number.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 3, then 2 is a divisor for at least two numbers.
        // For example, if l=3, r=5, numbers are {3,4,5}. Divisor 2 for {4}. Count=1.
        // Divisor 3 for {3}. Count=1. Divisor 4 for {4}. Count=1. Divisor 5 for {5}. Count=1.
        // In this case, any of 2,3,4,5 is a valid answer.
        //
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, the number 2 will always be a divisor for at least one number.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 3, the number 2 will always be a divisor for at least two numbers.
        //
        // The maximum possible count for any divisor d is floor(r/d) - floor((l-1)/d).
        // This count is maximized when d is minimized.
        // Since divisors must be > 1, the smallest possible divisor is 2.
        // Therefore, 2 will always be the integer that appears the maximum number of times
        // as a divisor, or tied for the maximum.
        //
        // The only edge case is when l == r. In this case, the only number is l.
        // Its divisors (excluding 1) are its prime factors and their combinations.
        // The problem asks for *any* integer that appears the maximum number of times.
        // If l == r, then l itself is a divisor of l (if l > 1).
        // Any prime factor of l would also be a divisor.
        // For example, if l=6, divisors are 2, 3, 6. All appear once.
        // The problem statement says "For all integers from l to r, inclusive, we wrote down all of their integer divisors except 1."
        // If l=r=6, the numbers are {6}. Divisors are {2,3,6}. All appear once.
        // Any of 2,3,6 is a valid answer.
        // The example output for 3 6 is 3.
        // The example output for 19 29 is 2.
        //
        // If l == r, any divisor of l (other than 1) would be a valid answer.
        // The simplest is to just output l itself (if l > 1).
        // The problem constraints are 2 <= l <= r. So l is always > 1.
        //
        // If l < r, then the range contains at least two numbers.
        // In this case, 2 is always the best choice or tied for the best.
        // For example, if l=3, r=6. Numbers are {3,4,5,6}.
        // Divisor 2: {4,6} -> count 2.
        // Divisor 3: {3,6} -> count 2.
        // Divisor 4: {4} -> count 1.
        // Divisor 5: {5} -> count 1.
        // Divisor 6: {6} -> count 1.
        // Both 2 and 3 give count 2. Outputting 2 is valid.
        //
        // So, if l == r, output l.
        // If l < r, output 2.

        std::cout << 2 << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

